{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015K21TdzuVWtkHWqxR5AMKF","type":"tool_result","content":"105\t  callers directly construct arbitrary DDL payloads.\n106\t\n107\t## Canonical identity and supersession\n108\t\n109\tFolded 2026-05-12 from archived `design-detailed-supersession.md` +\n110\t`design-id-generation-policy.md` per the Phase 1a learnings disposition\n111\t(`learnings.md:94, 98`). This section is the authoritative home for the\n112\t0.6.0 canonical identity contract.\n113\t\n114\t### Identity model\n115\t\n116\tCanonical rows separate physical row identity from logical entity identity:\n117\t\n118\t- `row_id` — identifies one physical version of a node, edge, chunk, run,\n119\t  step, or action. Globally unique.\n120\t- `logical_id` — identifies the application entity across versions. Stable\n121\t  across supersessions. Required on `NodeInsert` and `EdgeInsert`; chunk /\n122\t  run / step / action use the single `id` field which is both physical and\n123\t  logical (these row kinds are not superseded in 0.6.0).\n124\t- The **active** version is the row for a given `logical_id` whose\n125\t  `superseded_at IS NULL`.\n126\t- A partial unique index enforces at most one active row per `logical_id`\n127\t  per kind.\n128\t\n129\tEdges reference logical identities; traversals resolve to the current\n130\tactive endpoint at read time.\n131\t\n132\t### ID generation policy\n133\t\n134\tCaller-owned IDs. The engine does not generate, assign, or sequence IDs as\n135\tpart of the write path:\n136\t\n137\t- Callers MUST provide `row_id` and `logical_id` on every `NodeInsert` and\n138\t  `EdgeInsert`.\n139\t- Callers MUST provide `id` on every `ChunkInsert`, `RunInsert`,\n140\t  `StepInsert`, and `ActionInsert`.\n141\t- Empty or duplicate-within-request IDs are rejected at `prepare_write`\n142\t  validation as a `WriteValidationError`, not at SQLite execution time.\n143\t- Cross-request uniqueness violations surface as the typed SQLite-mapped\n144\t  error per `design/errors.md`.\n145\t\n146\tRationale: caller-owned IDs preserve idempotent replay, keep the engine\n147\tstateless for ID sequencing, and let supersession address rows by stable\n148\t`logical_id` without a query round-trip.\n149\t\n150\tThe engine ships a standalone `new_id() -> String` utility (26-character\n151\tULID) for callers that lack their own ID scheme. The utility is not part\n152\tof the write path; callers with existing identifiers do not need it.\n153\t\n154\t### Write semantics under supersession\n155\t\n156\tEach accepted batch executes one SQLite transaction (see \"Batch submission\n157\tsemantics\" below). Within that transaction, supersession proceeds as:\n158\t\n159\t1. Validate canonical rows and references.\n160\t2. Append new physical rows (nodes, edges, chunks, runs, steps, actions).\n161\t3. For each replaced `logical_id`, mark the prior active row superseded\n162\t   (`superseded_at = <commit timestamp>`); do NOT mutate the prior row's\n163\t   value columns.\n164\t4. Enqueue derived-projection invalidation for affected logical ids and\n165\t   kinds (FTS rows for retired chunks, vector rows for retired nodes).\n166\t5. Commit, or roll the entire batch back.\n167\t\n168\tSupersession preserves both the old and the new physical row as separate\n169\tfacts. The old row is marked inactive; its content is not rewritten.\n170\t\n171\t### Restoration as a canonical write\n172\t\n173\t\"Restore a `logical_id`\" means making a previously superseded physical row\n174\tactive again. The 0.6.0 restoration operator (`Engine::restore_logical_id`,\n175\trecovery-only — see `design/recovery.md`) appends a new active row that\n176\tpreserves restore provenance rather than mutating the historical\n177\t`superseded_at` column. The replay source is the op-store\n178\t`append_only_log` write history for the logical id (see\n179\t`design/recovery.md § Logical-id purge and restore`).\n180\t\n181\t### Projection invariants\n182\t\n183\tProjections follow canonical active state:\n184\t\n185\t- FTS rows derive from active chunks; supersession retires the\n186\t  corresponding FTS row.\n187\t- Per-kind vector rows (`vec_<kind>`) derive from active nodes;\n188\t  supersession retires the corresponding vector row.\n189\t- A canonical row whose `superseded_at IS NOT NULL` has no derived\n190\t  projection rows for that logical id and kind.\n191\t\n192\tRecovery tooling (`recover --rebuild-projections`, `--rebuild-vec0`)\n193\trebuilds projections from the active canonical state, not from history.\n194\t\n195\t## Batch submission semantics\n196\t\n197\t`Engine.write(&[PreparedWrite])` is one ordered writer submission in 0.6.0.\n198\t\n199\tThe contract is:"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4e0d30c0-d2ee-4cef-baf2-390d4427d50f","uuid":"e8fa0b6a-ab87-451c-8192-6ad23e743afb","timestamp":"2026-05-16T13:10:49.953Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-10b-B-purge-restore-20260516T131040Z/dev/design/engine.md","content":"  callers directly construct arbitrary DDL payloads.\n\n## Canonical identity and supersession\n\nFolded 2026-05-12 from archived `design-detailed-supersession.md` +\n`design-id-generation-policy.md` per the Phase 1a learnings disposition\n(`learnings.md:94, 98`). This section is the authoritative home for the\n0.6.0 canonical identity contract.\n\n### Identity model\n\nCanonical rows separate physical row identity from logical entity identity:\n\n- `row_id` — identifies one physical version of a node, edge, chunk, run,\n  step, or action. Globally unique.\n- `logical_id` — identifies the application entity across versions. Stable\n  across supersessions. Required on `NodeInsert` and `EdgeInsert`; chunk /\n  run / step / action use the single `id` field which is both physical and\n  logical (these row kinds are not superseded in 0.6.0).\n- The **active** version is the row for a given `logical_id` whose\n  `superseded_at IS NULL`.\n- A partial unique index enforces at most one active row per `logical_id`\n  per kind.\n\nEdges reference logical identities; traversals resolve to the current\nactive endpoint at read time.\n\n### ID generation policy\n\nCaller-owned IDs. The engine does not generate, assign, or sequence IDs as\npart of the write path:\n\n- Callers MUST provide `row_id` and `logical_id` on every `NodeInsert` and\n  `EdgeInsert`.\n- Callers MUST provide `id` on every `ChunkInsert`, `RunInsert`,\n  `StepInsert`, and `ActionInsert`.\n- Empty or duplicate-within-request IDs are rejected at `prepare_write`\n  validation as a `WriteValidationError`, not at SQLite execution time.\n- Cross-request uniqueness violations surface as the typed SQLite-mapped\n  error per `design/errors.md`.\n\nRationale: caller-owned IDs preserve idempotent replay, keep the engine\nstateless for ID sequencing, and let supersession address rows by stable\n`logical_id` without a query round-trip.\n\nThe engine ships a standalone `new_id() -> String` utility (26-character\nULID) for callers that lack their own ID scheme. The utility is not part\nof the write path; callers with existing identifiers do not need it.\n\n### Write semantics under supersession\n\nEach accepted batch executes one SQLite transaction (see \"Batch submission\nsemantics\" below). Within that transaction, supersession proceeds as:\n\n1. Validate canonical rows and references.\n2. Append new physical rows (nodes, edges, chunks, runs, steps, actions).\n3. For each replaced `logical_id`, mark the prior active row superseded\n   (`superseded_at = <commit timestamp>`); do NOT mutate the prior row's\n   value columns.\n4. Enqueue derived-projection invalidation for affected logical ids and\n   kinds (FTS rows for retired chunks, vector rows for retired nodes).\n5. Commit, or roll the entire batch back.\n\nSupersession preserves both the old and the new physical row as separate\nfacts. The old row is marked inactive; its content is not rewritten.\n\n### Restoration as a canonical write\n\n\"Restore a `logical_id`\" means making a previously superseded physical row\nactive again. The 0.6.0 restoration operator (`Engine::restore_logical_id`,\nrecovery-only — see `design/recovery.md`) appends a new active row that\npreserves restore provenance rather than mutating the historical\n`superseded_at` column. The replay source is the op-store\n`append_only_log` write history for the logical id (see\n`design/recovery.md § Logical-id purge and restore`).\n\n### Projection invariants\n\nProjections follow canonical active state:\n\n- FTS rows derive from active chunks; supersession retires the\n  corresponding FTS row.\n- Per-kind vector rows (`vec_<kind>`) derive from active nodes;\n  supersession retires the corresponding vector row.\n- A canonical row whose `superseded_at IS NOT NULL` has no derived\n  projection rows for that logical id and kind.\n\nRecovery tooling (`recover --rebuild-projections`, `--rebuild-vec0`)\nrebuilds projections from the active canonical state, not from history.\n\n## Batch submission semantics\n\n`Engine.write(&[PreparedWrite])` is one ordered writer submission in 0.6.0.\n\nThe contract is:","numLines":95,"startLine":105,"totalLines":313}}}
